• The organization expects its unstructured storage to grow 20-49% in the next 12 months. Headquartered in New York, NY, Marsh & McLennan Companies, Inc. (MMC) is a global professional services firm. Through the company's business units, MMC operates in four market segments: Risk and Insurance Services, Risk Consulting and Technology, Consulting, and Investment Management. The company's major business units include: Marsh, Oliver Wyman, Mercer, and Guy Carpenter.

IT INTELLIGENCE •The company is going to be increasing its focus on developing customer facing applications. •The biggest pain point for the IT group is enhanced customer experience functionality.
IT STRUCTURE
At the Marsh & McLennan Companies, Inc (MMC) headquarters in New York, the majority of Information Technology (IT) employees work in the company's Global Technology Infrastructure Team. The company's data center, however, is located in Franklin, MA. Subsidiary Mercer Consulting Services has its own separate IT staff in the U.S. and Canada; however, Mercer's IT is still mostly entwined with MMC's IT group. Another subsidiary, Guy Carpenter, uses UBICS consulting firm for purchasing some of its IT products and services. Subsidiary Oliver Wyman is maintained as separate profile in RainKing.

IT INFORMATION BYTES

•    The company relies on IBM WebSphere as its central integration server and application portal. Additionally, IT supports other various IBM hardware and systems.
•    The company is continually examining data center virtualizations, virtualizing servers with VMware as the need arises. The company also uses Oracle 11g.
•    As of early 2013, Marsh & McLennan's network group also indicates there are plans to increase mobility spending in the areas of network management tools, mobile device management software, support, and security.
•    The IT budget is typically finalized in Q3.
•    2013:
    •>5 pb data volume company-wide across 6 to 10 data centers, and expects an annual data growth of 11-20%.
    •10-24% of its servers are to be virtualized by the end of 2013.
    •Corporate IT manages 12000 mobile devices.
    •Corporate IT manages 65000 desktops.
    •Cost is the primary consideration for buying hardware.
    •Data center strategy is centered on whatever is best for applications – VMs/standalone server/custom hardware appliance.
    •Long term plan for running new applications is to add servers and virtualize, but no new facilities are scheduled.





